Q)Explain ConcurrentModificationException in Java

âœ…ï¸Ans)

The ConcurrentModificationException occurs when a collection is modified while being iterated using an iterator or enhanced for-loop.

â“ï¸When Does It Happen?

âŒï¸It happens when:

You modify a collection (like ArrayList, HashMap) while iterating over it using an iterator.

ğŸ§¶You modify a collection (like ArrayList, HashMap) while iterating over it using an iterator.

ğŸ§¶The iterator detects the structural modification and throws ConcurrentModificationException.

ğŸ—³Example:
ğŸ‘‡
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
 list.add("A");
 list.add("B");
 list.add("C");
 // Iterating using for-each loop
 for (String s : list) {
 if (s.equals("B")) {
 list.remove(s); // Throws ConcurrentModificationException
 }
 }

âŒï¸Why Does This Fail?

ğŸ”¹ï¸The for-each loop uses an Iterator internally.

ğŸ”¹ï¸The remove(s) modifies the list while iterating.

ğŸ”¹ï¸The Iterator detects this modification and throws ConcurrentModificationException.

âŒï¸How to Avoid ConcurrentModificationException?

âœ… Method 1: Use Iterator.remove()
âœ…ï¸ Method 2: UseCopyOnWriteArrayList (Thread-Safe)
âœ… Method 3 :Iterate backward to avoid shifting issues.
âœ…Method 4:Use ConcurrentHashMap for safe concurrent operations.
